Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aTracing women's experiences of miscarriage and termination for foetal anomaly in the second trimester, before legal viability, shows how such events are positioned as less 'real' or significant when the foetal being does not, or will not, survive. Invisible Labours describes the reproductive politics of this category of pregnancy loss in England. It shows how second trimester pregnancy loss produces specific medical and social experiences, revealing an underlying teleological ontology of pregnancy. Some women then understand their pregnancy through kinship with the unborn baby.  afunded by Economic and Social Research Council & the Wellcome Centre for Cultures and Environments of Health  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbortionxSocial aspectszEngland. 0aFetusxLegal status, laws, etczEngland. 0aFetusxLegal status, laws, etc.zEngland. 0aMiscarriagexSocial aspectszEngland. 0aPregnancyxComplications. 0aPregnancyxTrimester, Second. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh2 aEconomic and Social Research Council & the Wellcome Centre for Cultures and Environments of Health efunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311133229140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781805392118zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781805392118zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781805392118/original  a978-3-11-133229-1 Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA